[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:19.852 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.852 --> 00:00:21.810 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
back to another edition

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:22.610 align:middle line:10%
of "Beyond Belief."

00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:26.010 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory, and this
is a very important show.

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:29.840 align:middle line:10%
Of course they all are, but
this one is very important

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:32.750 align:middle line:10%
as we're going to talk about
emergency planning and crisis

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:36.920 align:middle line:10%
management, things that will
help you during an emergency.

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:41.520 align:middle line:84%
Our special guest
is Matthew Stein.

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:43.510 align:middle line:84%
>>We are at a key
moment in history,

00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:45.360 align:middle line:84%
and our choices will
determine whether we

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:48.080 align:middle line:84%
are headed for the
collapse of civilization

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:50.100 align:middle line:90%
or a global Renaissance.

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:52.940 align:middle line:10%
Matthew Stein, author of
two best selling books,

00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:56.970 align:middle line:10%
"When Disaster Strikes" and
"When Technology Fails,"

00:00:56.970 --> 00:01:00.900 align:middle line:10%
says it's still up to us,
though time is running out.

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:03.200 align:middle line:84%
Matt warns of a
half dozen scenarios

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:05.519 align:middle line:84%
looming on the horizon,
any one of which

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:09.390 align:middle line:84%
would result in a civilization
busting catastrophe.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:12.610 align:middle line:84%
But he hopes his vision for
a more sustainable future

00:01:12.610 --> 00:01:15.450 align:middle line:84%
will inspire us to move
in the right direction

00:01:15.450 --> 00:01:17.160 align:middle line:90%
before it's too late.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:21.670 align:middle line:90%
Today, on "Beyond Belief."

00:01:21.670 --> 00:01:24.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And I've got one of his
books, "When Technology Fails,"

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:26.736 align:middle line:84%
and I'm keeping it
after this program.

00:01:26.736 --> 00:01:28.110 align:middle line:10%
You're not getting
it back, Matt.

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:29.010 align:middle line:10%
>>MATTHEW STEIN: OK.

00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:29.660 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: --at all.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:30.420 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: It's yours.

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:31.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me
about this and what

00:01:31.970 --> 00:01:33.740 align:middle line:84%
got you involved in
this, because you're

00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:35.900 align:middle line:90%
a designer by trade, right?

00:01:35.900 --> 00:01:38.310 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: Well, I'm a mechanical
engineer with a bachelor

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:39.830 align:middle line:10%
of science from MIT.

00:01:39.830 --> 00:01:43.700 align:middle line:10%
And in 1997, at
that point in time

00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:46.140 align:middle line:10%
I'd had a 20 year
practice of meditation.

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:48.410 align:middle line:10%
And in my morning
session of meditation

00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:51.280 align:middle line:10%
I made a generic request for
guidance and inspiration,

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:53.492 align:middle line:10%
just kind of like, OK, god,
what am I supposed to do?

00:01:53.492 --> 00:01:54.292 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:01:54.292 --> 00:01:57.510 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: And I got a bomb
dropped in my lap that morning.

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:01.170 align:middle line:84%
I received a pictorial
storyboard outline

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:05.380 align:middle line:84%
for a massive project to help
people live more sustainably,

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:08.169 align:middle line:84%
and also to help
people plan and cope

00:02:08.169 --> 00:02:13.510 align:middle line:84%
with major long-term failures in
our central services-- meaning,

00:02:13.510 --> 00:02:17.012 align:middle line:84%
no Costco, no gasoline, no
electricity, no water flowing.

00:02:17.012 --> 00:02:17.970 align:middle line:90%
How do we deal with it?

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:19.350 align:middle line:90%
How do we cope?

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:22.170 align:middle line:84%
Now my first thought, when
I received this vision,

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:23.780 align:middle line:90%
was no way.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:24.940 align:middle line:90%
I'm an engineer.

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:26.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm not an author.

00:02:26.230 --> 00:02:27.500 align:middle line:90%
I don't know all this stuff.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:29.580 align:middle line:90%
I can't possibly do this.

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:31.710 align:middle line:84%
And Jesus calls it the
still, small voice,

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:34.235 align:middle line:90%
other people, the inner voice.

00:02:34.235 --> 00:02:35.860 align:middle line:84%
The little voice in
my head said, well,

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:37.070 align:middle line:90%
nobody knows it all.

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.970 align:middle line:84%
And it assured me that I
had the skills and talents

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:42.530 align:middle line:84%
that if I chose to take
this assignment on that I'd

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:45.160 align:middle line:84%
get the inner and outer help
I needed to finish it off.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.300 align:middle line:84%
Now, I didn't just
jump right up and said,

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:50.524 align:middle line:84%
well, God inspired me
and talked to me today.

00:02:50.524 --> 00:02:52.940 align:middle line:84%
It took me about a year to
decide maybe is was a good idea

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:55.150 align:middle line:84%
and I could do it,
another year to start

00:02:55.150 --> 00:02:58.610 align:middle line:84%
reading 30 or 40 books,
start writing a proposal,

00:02:58.610 --> 00:02:59.640 align:middle line:90%
find a publisher.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.800 align:middle line:84%
And then in the last year,
I worked 70 hours a week

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:05.120 align:middle line:84%
seven days a week
to finish it off.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:07.670 align:middle line:84%
And what you see there is the
second edition of my book.

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:09.170 align:middle line:84%
You got about three
years in my life

00:03:09.170 --> 00:03:10.880 align:middle line:84%
and all the equity in
my home in that book.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:11.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right here.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:12.560 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: That's right.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:15.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: William Forstchen,
one of our past guests

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.410 align:middle line:84%
on the program, has
talked about what

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:20.470 align:middle line:84%
would happen if we had
an EMP attack-- that's

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:23.530 align:middle line:84%
an electromagnetic
pulse bomb that blows up

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:26.020 align:middle line:84%
over the atmosphere--
or a solar flare that

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:27.710 align:middle line:90%
takes out the power grid.

00:03:27.710 --> 00:03:30.430 align:middle line:84%
A lot of that is
right down your alley.

00:03:30.430 --> 00:03:35.020 align:middle line:84%
Because if we lose the ability
to have electrical power

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:37.390 align:middle line:90%
we're up a creek, Matt.

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:40.120 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Yet the EMP
Commission estimates

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:43.120 align:middle line:84%
that 90% of the population
of the United States

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:45.480 align:middle line:84%
would probably perish
in the first year

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:50.680 align:middle line:84%
after either an extreme solar
event or a nuclear EMP attack.

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:53.190 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: 200+ million people
dead after the first year.

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:56.170 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: You're talking maybe
even 300 million people dead

00:03:56.170 --> 00:03:58.820 align:middle line:10%
after the first year.

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:01.540 align:middle line:84%
There's a good news,
bad news scenario.

00:04:01.540 --> 00:04:05.290 align:middle line:84%
The good news is that there
are technological fixes

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:06.310 align:middle line:90%
to mitigate this.

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:08.550 align:middle line:84%
Not to say that an
EMP or a solar attack

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:11.910 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't be severe, even with
the best efforts they could do,

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:13.690 align:middle line:84%
but for a couple
of billion dollars,

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:16.010 align:middle line:84%
the price of a single
stealth bomber,

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:19.362 align:middle line:84%
they could fix the grid so it
wouldn't be all-out collapse,

00:04:19.362 --> 00:04:21.320 align:middle line:84%
and they could protect
our nuclear power plants

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:23.930 align:middle line:84%
from meltdowns in
the event of an EMP.

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:27.570 align:middle line:84%
The bad news is that so far
they're just talking about it.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:31.230 align:middle line:84%
So, much like the US Army
Corps of Engineers warned

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:35.090 align:middle line:84%
for 50 years that the
levees around New Orleans

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:39.720 align:middle line:84%
were not adequate to sustain
a category 3 or stronger storm

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:41.805 align:middle line:84%
and that they would
fail, the government

00:04:41.805 --> 00:04:44.180 align:middle line:84%
knew there was a problem and
they talked about fixing it,

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.610 align:middle line:84%
but they never fixed it
and the problem happened.

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:49.690 align:middle line:10%
The problem with the grid
is that, similarly, they're

00:04:49.690 --> 00:04:52.640 align:middle line:10%
talking about the problem,
the scientists acknowledge

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:55.630 align:middle line:10%
the problem, but they're
still just talking

00:04:55.630 --> 00:04:57.490 align:middle line:10%
and they haven't
implemented the fixes.

00:04:57.490 --> 00:05:01.260 align:middle line:84%
So it would be a shame if
the stock market collapsed,

00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:05.030 align:middle line:84%
the government collapsed, and
90% of the people of the United

00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:08.790 align:middle line:84%
States died because for the
price of a single stealth

00:05:08.790 --> 00:05:11.230 align:middle line:84%
bomber we never got
around to making

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:12.314 align:middle line:90%
the decision of fixing it.

00:05:12.314 --> 00:05:13.146 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:05:13.146 --> 00:05:14.900 align:middle line:84%
What are other nations
doing, because they

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:16.066 align:middle line:90%
would have the same problem?

00:05:16.066 --> 00:05:19.780 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Well, what's
interesting is that,

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.100 align:middle line:84%
is often the case,
the United States

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:24.440 align:middle line:84%
is at the forefront of
identifying the problem,

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:26.220 align:middle line:90%
but we're dragging our feet.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.409 align:middle line:84%
So in some places,
in some countries,

00:05:28.409 --> 00:05:30.200 align:middle line:84%
they're working in the
EU-- and some places

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.860 align:middle line:84%
in the EU they're
working to fix the grid.

00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:34.890 align:middle line:84%
In the Soviet
Union and in China,

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.180 align:middle line:84%
they're working actively
to strengthen the grid

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:38.660 align:middle line:90%
against EMP and solar storms--

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:39.577 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Smart people.

00:05:39.577 --> 00:05:40.993 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: --and
we're not doing it.

00:05:40.993 --> 00:05:42.526 align:middle line:84%
So here our
scientists figured out

00:05:42.526 --> 00:05:44.150 align:middle line:84%
the problem, figured
out the solutions,

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:46.999 align:middle line:84%
but we're dragging
our feet to fix it.

00:05:46.999 --> 00:05:49.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You would think a
presidential candidate would

00:05:49.290 --> 00:05:51.980 align:middle line:84%
use this-- Newt Gingrich
did several years ago,

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:54.290 align:middle line:90%
but it fell on deaf ears.

00:05:54.290 --> 00:05:56.440 align:middle line:84%
That they would push
things like this

00:05:56.440 --> 00:06:01.310 align:middle line:84%
to get this done, instead of
the rabble rousing and the junk

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:02.224 align:middle line:90%
they talk about.

00:06:02.224 --> 00:06:03.390 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: You would think so.

00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:07.870 align:middle line:90%


00:06:07.870 --> 00:06:10.140 align:middle line:84%
The state of Maine
is the only state

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:12.770 align:middle line:84%
that's actively doing
something to fix and strengthen

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:16.780 align:middle line:84%
their grid, and they had some
people who ran on this platform

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:18.500 align:middle line:84%
and actually got
elected on this.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.420 align:middle line:84%
But unfortunately
in the government

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:22.510 align:middle line:84%
so far, they're just
kind of ignoring it.

00:06:22.510 --> 00:06:24.490 align:middle line:84%
They don't think it's
that big of an issue.

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:27.740 align:middle line:84%
And part of the problem was
when the EMP Commission said

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.780 align:middle line:84%
this is a huge problem,
there's a private corporation

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:34.470 align:middle line:84%
called National Electric
Reliability Corporation.

00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Sounds like they're the good
guys and in a sense they are.

00:06:38.470 --> 00:06:41.320 align:middle line:84%
It's a group of people
from the industry ensuring

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:43.550 align:middle line:90%
that our grid is healthy.

00:06:43.550 --> 00:06:47.890 align:middle line:84%
And NERC came out after
the EMP Commission came out

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:48.690 align:middle line:90%
with their stuff.

00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:52.030 align:middle line:84%
They had a forum and
they'd identified

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:54.940 align:middle line:84%
that EMP and solar storm were
huge threats to the grid.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:57.030 align:middle line:84%
And they wrote a report
called "The HILF Report"--

00:06:57.030 --> 00:06:59.320 align:middle line:90%
high impact, low frequency.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:01.370 align:middle line:84%
They said, these are
event, black swan events,

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:03.160 align:middle line:90%
that are really serious.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.452 align:middle line:84%
After that report came
out, NERC fired those guys

00:07:05.452 --> 00:07:06.410 align:middle line:90%
that wrote the report--

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:07.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh, my.

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:08.263 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: --had new people.

00:07:08.263 --> 00:07:10.350 align:middle line:10%
They wrote a new report
saying everything's OK--

00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:11.891 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Yeah, that's
what they want.

00:07:11.891 --> 00:07:13.400 align:middle line:10%
That was their mission.

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:15.360 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: --that our
existing safeguards are OK.

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:18.840 align:middle line:84%
But the truth of the
matter is, in 1989

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:23.510 align:middle line:84%
we had a storm that was
one-tenth as strong as the 1921

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:24.650 align:middle line:90%
geomagnetic storm.

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:27.572 align:middle line:84%
That's called the Great
Geomagnetic Storm of 1921.

00:07:27.572 --> 00:07:29.030 align:middle line:10%
And the prior one
before that was--

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:30.405 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Carrington
Event, right?

00:07:30.405 --> 00:07:34.080 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: The 1859 Carrington
Event, 50% stronger

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:35.690 align:middle line:10%
than the 1921 storm.

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:39.390 align:middle line:84%
So in the last 160 years,
we've had two giant storms.

00:07:39.390 --> 00:07:41.700 align:middle line:84%
A storm that was
one-tenth as strong

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:47.020 align:middle line:84%
as the smaller of those two
caused 15 simultaneous failures

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:50.640 align:middle line:84%
in the province of Quebec,
wiped out a massive transformer

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:51.440 align:middle line:90%
in Quebec.

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:52.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:54.550 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: It caused power to go
out in the entire province--

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:55.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Millions
were without power.

00:07:55.220 --> 00:07:57.070 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Millions
were without power,

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:58.980 align:middle line:90%
and that's one-tenth as strong.

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:01.890 align:middle line:84%
The U.S. Government
funded a study

00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:05.540 align:middle line:84%
to look at the effects
of a geomagnetic storm,

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:07.390 align:middle line:84%
and they based it
on the 1921 one,

00:08:07.390 --> 00:08:10.400 align:middle line:84%
which they estimate is
a one in 80 year event.

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:14.180 align:middle line:84%
You know, roughly 70-80 year
event; 75 years, approximately.

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:17.660 align:middle line:84%
That storm, when they
did the computer models,

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:21.510 align:middle line:84%
they estimated that 350 of
the massive transformers

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.380 align:middle line:84%
in the United States
would go down.

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:26.820 align:middle line:84%
Now, these transformers
are 20 feet tall,

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:30.320 align:middle line:84%
hundreds of tons, tens of
millions of dollars each.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:32.250 align:middle line:84%
There's a three year
waiting line to get one.

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:34.280 align:middle line:84%
They're custom made
and custom built.

00:08:34.280 --> 00:08:36.740 align:middle line:84%
When one of those
transformers went down

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:38.630 align:middle line:84%
in Quebec, and a
few smaller things,

00:08:38.630 --> 00:08:40.460 align:middle line:90%
the whole province went out.

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:43.450 align:middle line:84%
If 350 go out in this
country, probably a couple

00:08:43.450 --> 00:08:47.240 align:middle line:84%
thousand in the world, that's 20
years of manufacturing capacity

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:49.200 align:middle line:90%
to replace those transformers.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.660 align:middle line:10%
And most of those will be
made in countries that will

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:53.260 align:middle line:10%
be crippled by the solar storm.

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:54.310 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Like China?

00:08:54.310 --> 00:08:55.920 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: Like China.

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:57.700 align:middle line:10%
Brazil might be OK.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:08:59.267 align:middle line:10%
They make them in Brazil now.

00:08:59.267 --> 00:09:00.350 align:middle line:10%
They make them in Germany.

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:00.950 align:middle line:10%
They won't be made.

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:02.310 align:middle line:84%
They're not even made
in America anymore.

00:09:02.310 --> 00:09:04.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They can't
make them fast enough.

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:08.480 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: Well imagine that
20 years, if we built them

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:10.859 align:middle line:10%
at today's rate, it
would take 20 years

00:09:10.859 --> 00:09:12.400 align:middle line:10%
