the world-- the Great Barrier

00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:56.980 align:middle line:90%
Reef out of Australia.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:58.650 align:middle line:90%
And they're bleached.

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:00.200 align:middle line:84%
Most of those
reefs are bleached.

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:03.230 align:middle line:84%
It's questionable whether
they will ever come back.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.660 align:middle line:84%
And if they do come
back short-term,

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:09.420 align:middle line:84%
the trends of the increasing
ocean temperatures

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:11.960 align:middle line:84%
is that long-term it
means they're probably

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:13.160 align:middle line:90%
going to be dead and gone.

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:15.470 align:middle line:84%
And huge numbers of the
populations of the world

00:19:15.470 --> 00:19:18.870 align:middle line:84%
rely on fish that are born and
spawned and raised in the coral

00:19:18.870 --> 00:19:19.670 align:middle line:90%
reefs.

00:19:19.670 --> 00:19:21.160 align:middle line:90%
So it's a giant system.

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:24.690 align:middle line:84%
And the reefs are like the
rain forests of the ocean.

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:26.510 align:middle line:10%
They're part of the
carbon oxygen cycle

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:29.630 align:middle line:10%
that keeps the atmosphere
breathable and livable.

00:19:29.630 --> 00:19:32.210 align:middle line:10%
And on top of that, we're
acidifying the oceans.

00:19:32.210 --> 00:19:34.670 align:middle line:10%
When we burn carbon
into the atmosphere

00:19:34.670 --> 00:19:38.260 align:middle line:10%
through our fossil fuels,
burning coal, burning oil,

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:40.030 align:middle line:10%
deforestation.

00:19:40.030 --> 00:19:43.140 align:middle line:10%
Carbon goes in the atmosphere,
the rain combines with it

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:44.620 align:middle line:10%
and makes carbolic acid.

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:46.930 align:middle line:10%
It falls down in the
oceans and into the rivers.

00:19:46.930 --> 00:19:50.020 align:middle line:10%
It acidifies the oceans and
the rivers and the lakes.

00:19:50.020 --> 00:19:52.530 align:middle line:84%
And right now the
pH of the ocean

00:19:52.530 --> 00:19:55.310 align:middle line:84%
is gradually getting
more and more acidic

00:19:55.310 --> 00:19:58.770 align:middle line:84%
and it's starting to cause
huge failures in shellfish.

00:19:58.770 --> 00:20:03.500 align:middle line:84%
There's places in British
Columbia where giant shellfish

00:20:03.500 --> 00:20:06.000 align:middle line:84%
zones where they grow the
shellfish, the scallops

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.950 align:middle line:84%
and the clams, they're
dying because that pH just

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:13.150 align:middle line:84%
changes a tiny little bit
and it disrupts the balance.

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:16.000 align:middle line:84%
They have limestone, they
have calcium structures

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.240 align:middle line:84%
that they rely on, and
the pH dissolves them

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:19.040 align:middle line:90%
and they're dying.

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:20.390 align:middle line:90%
So we're killing the oceans.

00:20:20.390 --> 00:20:23.360 align:middle line:84%
The forests-- half of
the world's forests

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:26.710 align:middle line:84%
have disappeared, most of
that in the last 50 years,

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:29.160 align:middle line:84%
and a good part of the
other half of the forests

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:30.650 align:middle line:90%
are being compromised.

00:20:30.650 --> 00:20:34.320 align:middle line:84%
And the rain forests are being
destroyed at very high rates.

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:37.470 align:middle line:84%
In spite of efforts to stop
it, they're not stopping it.

