Clorox bleach won't kill.

00:27:57.010 --> 00:27:59.820 align:middle line:84%
But if it's clear water,
I take this SteriPEN

00:27:59.820 --> 00:28:02.470 align:middle line:84%
in-- it's kind of like the
little pen in "Men In Black"

00:28:02.470 --> 00:28:05.440 align:middle line:84%
when he gives the flashy thing
and their memory goes away.

00:28:05.440 --> 00:28:08.380 align:middle line:84%
I stick it in the water
and I stir it around.

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:10.620 align:middle line:84%
And when these
sensors detect water,

00:28:10.620 --> 00:28:12.870 align:middle line:84%
that it's submerged
in there, a blue light

00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:15.602 align:middle line:84%
goes on and in 15 seconds
all the bugs are dead.

00:28:15.602 --> 00:28:17.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So when you
stick that in there,

00:28:17.310 --> 00:28:18.226 align:middle line:90%
what does it do, Matt?

00:28:18.226 --> 00:28:20.390 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: When you stick
it in there like this,

00:28:20.390 --> 00:28:23.240 align:middle line:84%
the blue light goes off
and you stir it around.

00:28:23.240 --> 00:28:27.260 align:middle line:84%
And it's a UV sterilizing light
and it kills all the bugs.

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:30.470 align:middle line:84%
And you stir it so to make sure
the water circulates around

00:28:30.470 --> 00:28:32.220 align:middle line:84%
so if there's little
tiny particles

00:28:32.220 --> 00:28:34.730 align:middle line:84%
that the light gets behind
those and kills them.

00:28:34.730 --> 00:28:39.720 align:middle line:84%
Now, all bets are off-- if you
have some scummy, green water,

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:41.029 align:middle line:90%
don't use your SteriPEN.

00:28:41.029 --> 00:28:42.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's for the filter.

00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:43.950 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: You need the filter.

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.220 align:middle line:84%
And if you're really
scared about the water,

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:48.760 align:middle line:84%
like, there's some nasty thing
and you see people dropping

00:28:48.760 --> 00:28:52.840 align:middle line:84%
dead around you, then I'd
filter it first so it's clear,

00:28:52.840 --> 00:28:55.070 align:middle line:84%
and then double hit
it with the SteriPEN.

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:58.600 align:middle line:84%
And then anything that survived
the filter, if there's a virus,

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:02.120 align:middle line:84%
this filter will get most of
the viruses and all the bacteria

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:04.710 align:middle line:84%
and all the protozoa
out of the water.

00:29:04.710 --> 00:29:06.960 align:middle line:84%
But the ones that are super
fine that filter viruses--

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:08.543 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's what
you use that for.

00:29:08.543 --> 00:29:09.920 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: --they
plug up too fast.

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:12.890 align:middle line:84%
In this one, you can take it
apart and field service it.

00:29:12.890 --> 00:29:16.290 align:middle line:84%
The first time you put your
viral filter in a scummy ditch,

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:18.470 align:middle line:84%
it's probably going to
be plugged and worthless.

00:29:18.470 --> 00:29:19.470 align:middle line:90%
That's why I like this.

00:29:19.470 --> 00:29:22.325 align:middle line:84%
Because without any hand
tools, you can field service it

00:29:22.325 --> 00:29:23.670 align:middle line:90%
and get it going again.

00:29:23.670 --> 00:29:25.020 align:middle line:90%
And then this is my backup.

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:27.790 align:middle line:84%
If I'm really worried, like,
some scary thing that's

00:29:27.790 --> 00:29:29.800 align:middle line:84%
killing people, I'll
zap it with this

00:29:29.800 --> 00:29:31.190 align:middle line:84%
after I've filtered
it with that.

00:29:31.190 --> 00:29:33.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why don't you
always do that anyway?

00:29:33.430 --> 00:29:34.761 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: Well--

00:29:34.761 --> 00:29:36.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It won't hurt, right?

00:29:36.010 --> 00:29:37.000 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: It won't hurt.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:41.920 align:middle line:84%
When my daughter went to
Africa with her future husband,

00:29:41.920 --> 00:29:47.090 align:middle line:84%
they went to Tanzania and he
was working in a medical clinic.

00:29:47.090 --> 00:29:50.790 align:middle line:84%
And they went up Kilimanjaro
and she took my SteriPEN.

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:52.650 align:middle line:84%
And she religiously
used the SteriPEN,

00:29:52.650 --> 00:29:53.677 align:middle line:90%
and not everybody did.

00:29:53.677 --> 00:29:56.010 align:middle line:84%
And she's the only one who
didn't get sick in the group.

00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:57.010 align:middle line:90%
She SteriPENed--

00:29:57.010 --> 00:29:57.270 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:29:57.270 --> 00:29:59.730 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: --everything that she
drank, and she never got sick.

00:29:59.730 --> 00:30:00.810 align:middle line:90%
Everybody else got sick.

00:30:00.810 --> 00:30:02.360 align:middle line:90%
They all got dysentery.

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:04.297 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And what
is that called?

00:30:04.297 --> 00:30:05.630 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: A SteriPEN right there.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:06.556 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: SteriPEN.

00:30:06.556 --> 00:30:08.130 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: And it sterilizes it.

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And you can get these things in
any kind of back country store,

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:15.480 align:middle line:84%
like an REI, a Cabela's,
an Eastern Mountain Shorts.

00:30:15.480 --> 00:30:20.590 align:middle line:84%
And also online I have,
on whentechfails.com,

00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:22.950 align:middle line:84%
I have an article
posted on my website

00:30:22.950 --> 00:30:25.620 align:middle line:84%
called "Building the
Ultimate Survival Kit."

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:27.700 align:middle line:84%
So if you go to that
article, then you'll

00:30:27.700 --> 00:30:31.490 align:middle line:84%
see all of these items and many
more than I can show you today,

00:30:31.490 --> 00:30:34.500 align:middle line:84%
and they're all guaranteed
high quality things.

00:30:34.500 --> 00:30:36.250 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not selling
anything directly.

00:30:36.250 --> 00:30:37.649 align:middle line:90%
They're just links to buy them.

00:30:37.649 --> 00:30:39.690 align:middle line:84%
And you can know that it's
stuff that I recommend

00:30:39.690 --> 00:30:41.090 align:middle line:84%
and it's high quality
and will do the job.

00:30:41.090 --> 00:30:43.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But people should
put a pack together, right?

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:46.530 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: I highly recommend it.

00:30:46.530 --> 00:30:50.670 align:middle line:84%
A go bag, they call it
a 72-hour survival kit.

00:30:50.670 --> 00:30:53.590 align:middle line:84%
And it covers your
food, your clothing,

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:56.530 align:middle line:84%
your shelter, any
medicines you might need,

00:30:56.530 --> 00:30:59.670 align:middle line:84%
prescription medicines,
your entertainment,

00:30:59.670 --> 00:31:01.220 align:middle line:90%
maybe a deck of cards.

00:31:01.220 --> 00:31:04.010 align:middle line:84%
Something so that you
can put it on your back,

00:31:04.010 --> 00:31:06.350 align:middle line:84%
or hopefully you can
throw in your car,

00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:08.160 align:middle line:84%
and you and your
family will have

00:31:08.160 --> 00:31:09.820 align:middle line:84%
what they need for
at least three days

00:31:09.820 --> 00:31:10.861 align:middle line:90%
until things settle down.

00:31:10.861 --> 00:31:12.950 align:middle line:84%
Like, if you look
at Kobe, Japan,

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:15.050 align:middle line:84%
it was a week or more
before most people

00:31:15.050 --> 00:31:17.360 align:middle line:90%
had any kind of relief.

00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:19.030 align:middle line:84%
If you look at
Hurricane Katrina,

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:22.080 align:middle line:84%
it was about three or four days
before they got much relief.

00:31:22.080 --> 00:31:25.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How long do
you plan for this?

00:31:25.390 --> 00:31:26.599 align:middle line:90%
I mean, if a grid goes down--

00:31:26.599 --> 00:31:27.931 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: If the grid goes down--

00:31:27.931 --> 00:31:29.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It could
be indefinitely.

00:31:29.650 --> 00:31:33.670 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: If the grid goes down,
you're talking months to years

00:31:33.670 --> 00:31:35.750 align:middle line:90%
before life's back to normal.

00:31:35.750 --> 00:31:39.830 align:middle line:84%
And it may never come
back to totally normal.

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:42.260 align:middle line:90%
It depends on how bad.

00:31:42.260 --> 00:31:46.270 align:middle line:84%
For instance,
long-term grid down

00:31:46.270 --> 00:31:51.820 align:middle line:84%
can cause-- nuclear power plants
must keep themselves cooled.

00:31:51.820 --> 00:31:53.017 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:31:53.017 --> 00:31:54.850 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: It's not like
turning a switch off.

00:31:54.850 --> 00:31:55.975 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They'll melt down.

00:31:55.975 --> 00:31:58.240 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: So when a nuclear
power plant loses the grid,

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:00.850 align:middle line:84%
it goes into emergency
shutdown mode.

00:32:00.850 --> 00:32:04.180 align:middle line:84%
And backup generators come in,
and those backup generators

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:05.250 align:middle line:90%
are run on fuel.

00:32:05.250 --> 00:32:06.850 align:middle line:90%
They're run on diesel fuel.

00:32:06.850 --> 00:32:10.810 align:middle line:84%
And if those generators
fail, they run out of gas,

00:32:10.810 --> 00:32:14.310 align:middle line:84%
then the pumps stop running
that keeps nuclear power plant--

00:32:14.310 --> 00:32:15.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Cooled.

00:32:15.130 --> 00:32:18.660 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: --cool, and then you
have a Fukushima-like event.

00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:20.980 align:middle line:84%
Apparently in Fukushima,
the earthquake

00:32:20.980 --> 00:32:24.890 align:middle line:84%
itself did not cause the
meltdowns in the reactors.

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:28.110 align:middle line:84%
What happened is the
earthquake took down the grid.

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:31.420 align:middle line:84%
So all four-- they had four
out of the six reactors

00:32:31.420 --> 00:32:33.240 align:middle line:90%
in Fukushima were operating.

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:35.740 align:middle line:84%
So all four reactors
went into emergency mode

00:32:35.740 --> 00:32:38.005 align:middle line:84%
where the generators kicked
in, the pumps kicked in,

00:32:38.005 --> 00:32:39.380 align:middle line:84%
and they started
keeping it cool.

00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:40.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They all
worked for a while.

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:41.730 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: They all worked.

00:32:41.730 --> 00:32:43.870 align:middle line:84%
20 minutes later the
tsunami came along--

00:32:43.870 --> 00:32:46.804 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And wiped it out.

00:32:46.804 --> 00:32:49.610 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Five out of the six
banks of generators and pumps

00:32:49.610 --> 00:32:50.410 align:middle line:90%
were wiped out.

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:54.580 align:middle line:84%
One of those was on the uphill
side of the power plant,

00:32:54.580 --> 00:32:56.300 align:middle line:90%
and it stayed operating.

00:32:56.300 --> 00:32:59.800 align:middle line:84%
The other five out of
six generator banks

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:02.330 align:middle line:90%
were wiped out by the tsunami.

00:33:02.330 --> 00:33:03.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The perfect storm.

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:04.320 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: Right.

00:33:04.320 --> 00:33:07.280 align:middle line:84%
So two of those reactors
went into full meltdown.

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:10.600 align:middle line:84%
One of the reactors was
kept cool by the pumps.

00:33:10.600 --> 00:33:14.150 align:middle line:84%
And then they shuttled power
from one reactor to the next,

00:33:14.150 --> 00:33:16.320 align:middle line:84%
and they only had
a partial meltdown.

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:19.660 align:middle line:84%
So the problem with a
long-term down scenario,

00:33:19.660 --> 00:33:23.750 align:middle line:84%
like a solar storm or an
EMP, is that they only

00:33:23.750 --> 00:33:27.580 align:middle line:84%
have mandated to keep a
week of backup fuel on hand.

00:33:27.580 --> 00:33:30.110 align:middle line:84%
So in the long-term
grid down scenario,

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:33.820 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at not only the
disruption of your daily life,

00:33:33.820 --> 00:33:36.650 align:middle line:84%
you're also looking at the
potential for these power

00:33:36.650 --> 00:33:40.250 align:middle line:84%
plants-- 104, now down to
98 in the United States

00:33:40.250 --> 00:33:43.350 align:middle line:84%
operating nuclear power
plants-- running out of fuel,

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:47.120 align:middle line:84%
melting down, multiple
Fukushima-like events happening

00:33:47.120 --> 00:33:50.500 align:middle line:90%
across the United States.

00:33:50.500 --> 00:33:53.940 align:middle line:84%
In some of these
worst case scenarios,

00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:57.260 align:middle line:84%
we're never coming back and
you're going to be on your own.

00:33:57.260 --> 00:34:01.330 align:middle line:10%
Now, in the vision
I saw back in 1997

00:34:01.330 --> 00:34:04.340 align:middle line:10%
when I was instructed by
some higher power-- it never

00:34:04.340 --> 00:34:07.250 align:middle line:10%
identified itself-- to write
this book that became "When

00:34:07.250 --> 00:34:12.150 align:middle line:10%
Technology Fails," I was
shown a long-term collapse

00:34:12.150 --> 00:34:15.110 align:middle line:10%
where the electricity, the
water, none of that stuff

00:34:15.110 --> 00:34:16.500 align:middle line:10%
was working for a long time.

00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:20.270 align:middle line:10%
And I realized that even though
I have a bachelor of science

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:24.739 align:middle line:10%
from MIT, I have cast metal
the old-fashioned way,

00:34:24.739 --> 00:34:28.780 align:middle line:10%
I've machined parts in a mill
and a lave, I've blown glass,

00:34:28.780 --> 00:34:30.520 align:middle line:10%
I've done pit-fired pottery.

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:32.270 align:middle line:84%
Even though I've done
all of those things,

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:36.320 align:middle line:84%
I've been an outdoor enthusiast,
survived 10-day solo trips

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:38.310 align:middle line:84%
through the High Sierras
in below zero weather

00:34:38.310 --> 00:34:40.296 align:middle line:90%
at night in the deep snows.

00:34:40.296 --> 00:34:42.420 align:middle line:84%
With all of those skills
and all of that knowledge,

00:34:42.420 --> 00:34:44.760 align:middle line:84%
I realized if I was dropped
in the middle of the Amazon,

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:47.589 align:middle line:84%
I could not replicate anything
from our modern world.

00:34:47.589 --> 00:34:48.469 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Exactly.

00:34:48.469 --> 00:34:51.360 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: So in putting together
"When Technology Fails,"

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:55.130 align:middle line:84%
I looked at the
old-fashioned technologies

00:34:55.130 --> 00:34:59.500 align:middle line:84%
that, in our grandparents'
day, somebody in every town

00:34:59.500 --> 00:35:01.670 align:middle line:84%
knew how to make or
fabricate whatever

00:35:01.670 --> 00:35:04.994 align:middle line:84%
was needed for a reasonable
standard of living.

00:35:04.994 --> 00:35:06.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, I realize
that none of us are

00:35:06.410 --> 00:35:09.240 align:middle line:84%
going to be able to
replicate an electronic chip.

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:10.600 align:middle line:90%
We just simply can't do that.

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:11.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:35:11.400 --> 00:35:14.090 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: But we can replicate
the technologies of Abraham

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:16.460 align:middle line:84%
Lincoln's days and
the technologies

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:18.860 align:middle line:90%
of George Washington's days.

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:20.970 align:middle line:84%
So in "When Technology
Fails," I tried

00:35:20.970 --> 00:35:23.720 align:middle line:84%
to give the basics of how
to do all of those things

00:35:23.720 --> 00:35:26.910 align:middle line:84%
so that if things
really fell apart,

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:28.930 align:middle line:84%
not only could you
survive the short-term,

00:35:28.930 --> 00:35:31.470 align:middle line:84%
but in the long-term,
you could go back

00:35:31.470 --> 00:35:34.320 align:middle line:84%
at least to the pioneering
day technologies.

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:36.360 align:middle line:84%
Because most of us don't
know how to do that.

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:38.960 align:middle line:84%
In our grandparents' day, people
knew that stuff; nowadays,

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:39.760 align:middle line:90%
they don't.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:44.540 align:middle line:84%
So I tried to replicate that
so people could cope long-term.

00:35:44.540 --> 00:35:45.830 align:middle line:90%
And I hope it never happens.

00:35:45.830 --> 00:35:49.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not somebody who's
looking forward to a "Mad Max"

00:35:49.450 --> 00:35:51.450 align:middle line:90%
scenario or survivalist thing.

00:35:51.450 --> 00:35:53.980 align:middle line:84%
I really don't want to
ever have to shoot anybody.

00:35:53.980 --> 00:35:56.550 align:middle line:84%
I hope I never have to
shoot somebody in my life.

00:35:56.550 --> 00:35:58.380 align:middle line:84%
But I acknowledge
the possibility

00:35:58.380 --> 00:36:03.470 align:middle line:84%
that current trends indicate it
may and probably will happen.

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:05.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Matt,
what's the tape for?

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:09.070 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: This is probably
the most important item

00:36:09.070 --> 00:36:10.280 align:middle line:90%
in your grab-and-go kit.

00:36:10.280 --> 00:36:13.880 align:middle line:84%
This is inch and a half
cloth athletic tape.

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:16.480 align:middle line:84%
Now, what do you
see in a disaster?

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:18.410 align:middle line:84%
You see people
walking down the road.

00:36:18.410 --> 00:36:19.895 align:middle line:84%
If it's not that
big of a disaster,

00:36:19.895 --> 00:36:21.770 align:middle line:84%
they're in their cars,
and they're in hotels,

00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:23.140 align:middle line:90%
and they're in buses.

00:36:23.140 --> 00:36:27.400 align:middle line:84%
But in real disasters--
you look at Kobe, Japan,

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:30.866 align:middle line:84%
you look at Fukushima, you look
at different places-- people

00:36:30.866 --> 00:36:31.990 align:middle line:90%
are walking down the roads.

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:34.425 align:middle line:84%
Now, most of us,
if you're not used

00:36:34.425 --> 00:36:36.550 align:middle line:84%
to doing this all the time,
what's going to happen?

00:36:36.550 --> 00:36:37.860 align:middle line:84%
You walk a couple
miles down the road,

00:36:37.860 --> 00:36:39.276 align:middle line:84%
your feet are going
to blister up,

00:36:39.276 --> 00:36:41.870 align:middle line:84%
and then those blisters pop
and you're going nowhere.

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:44.520 align:middle line:84%
So what you do is, when you
feel the hot spots on your feet,

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:46.310 align:middle line:90%
you pull out your roll of tape.

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:49.460 align:middle line:84%
You take a little bit off
and you use the sticky side

00:36:49.460 --> 00:36:53.260 align:middle line:84%
to scrub the scummy grease
and dirt off of your heels.

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:54.820 align:middle line:84%
You tape your
heels, or your toes,

00:36:54.820 --> 00:36:56.140 align:middle line:90%
or wherever you have a problem.

00:36:56.140 --> 00:36:58.850 align:middle line:84%
Put your shoes and socks back
on and you're in business.

00:36:58.850 --> 00:37:00.810 align:middle line:84%
You get a sprained ankle,
you can tape it up.

00:37:00.810 --> 00:37:02.390 align:middle line:84%
You get a wound,
you can tape it up.

00:37:02.390 --> 00:37:06.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is probably the most
important item in the kit.

00:37:06.380 --> 00:37:09.870 align:middle line:84%
And this is one of the
other most important items,

00:37:09.870 --> 00:37:11.114 align:middle line:90%
because in a real disaster--

00:37:11.114 --> 00:37:12.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's like a
little TV antennae.

00:37:12.780 --> 00:37:13.580 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: Yeah.

00:37:13.580 --> 00:37:17.860 align:middle line:84%
What this is is you put this
into a big canteen or water

00:37:17.860 --> 00:37:20.980 align:middle line:84%
bottle, and you turn this
on-- it's a nine volt battery,

00:37:20.980 --> 00:37:23.680 align:middle line:84%
and I have a 12 volt
adapter-- and this

00:37:23.680 --> 00:37:24.990 align:middle line:90%
makes colloidal silver.

00:37:24.990 --> 00:37:26.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Ah, kills germs, right?

00:37:26.380 --> 00:37:27.410 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: It kills germs.

00:37:27.410 --> 00:37:29.630 align:middle line:90%
So what you have is broadband.

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:30.600 align:middle line:90%
It kills germs.

00:37:30.600 --> 00:37:35.376 align:middle line:84%
It may even help with viruses,
and it'll purify water

00:37:35.376 --> 00:37:36.500 align:middle line:90%
over a long period of time.

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:40.710 align:middle line:84%
But more importantly, if you
drink a quart of this a day--

00:37:40.710 --> 00:37:42.910 align:middle line:84%
and you can make that
in about 15 minutes--

00:37:42.910 --> 00:37:45.880 align:middle line:84%
if there's some really
nasty bug going on,

00:37:45.880 --> 00:37:48.670 align:middle line:90%
you will probably kill that bug.

00:37:48.670 --> 00:37:51.720 align:middle line:84%
Now, 2,000 years ago,
Alexander the Great

00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:53.940 align:middle line:84%
didn't know anything
about germ theory.

00:37:53.940 --> 00:37:56.800 align:middle line:84%
But he knew that if he
stored water for his troops

00:37:56.800 --> 00:38:00.010 align:middle line:84%
in silver urns that his
troops didn't get sick.

00:38:00.010 --> 00:38:03.410 align:middle line:84%
And a warrior on a battlefield
that had dysentery and was

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:07.510 align:middle line:84%
vomiting was a dead warrior,
but a warrior who was healthy

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:08.830 align:middle line:90%
stood a good chance.

00:38:08.830 --> 00:38:13.200 align:middle line:84%
So nowadays they've discovered
that tiny charred silver

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:17.900 align:middle line:84%
particles have this almost
magical property of being

00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:21.440 align:middle line:84%
deadly to all known
toxic bacteria,

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:23.430 align:middle line:90%
but not harmful to human beings.

00:38:23.430 --> 00:38:25.917 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's plenty of
metals that kill bacteria,

00:38:25.917 --> 00:38:27.250 align:middle line:90%
but they're also bad for people.

00:38:27.250 --> 00:38:27.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:30.340 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Silver is the one
metal that kills the bacteria

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:32.120 align:middle line:90%
but is not bad for people.

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:35.590 align:middle line:84%
And apparently, the same
extra thick cellular wall

00:38:35.590 --> 00:38:37.960 align:middle line:84%
that your probiotic
bacteria that's

00:38:37.960 --> 00:38:40.620 align:middle line:84%
so essential to good
digestion and to assimilating

00:38:40.620 --> 00:38:44.070 align:middle line:84%
your food, the same extra thick
cellular walls that protect

00:38:44.070 --> 00:38:47.180 align:middle line:84%
the probiotic bacteria
from your stomach acids

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:49.250 align:middle line:84%
also protects them
from the silver.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:52.850 align:middle line:10%
So it seems kind of like Santa
Claus, and the Tooth Fairy,

00:38:52.850 --> 00:38:55.170 align:middle line:10%
and the Easter Bunny,
like, too good to be true.

00:38:55.170 --> 00:38:58.400 align:middle line:10%
But colloidal silver does
not kill the good bacteria

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:00.520 align:middle line:10%
in your gut, but kills
the bad bacteria, so

00:39:00.520 --> 00:39:02.570 align:middle line:10%
a very important
item for your go-bag.

00:39:02.570 --> 00:39:04.770 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: And lastly,
what is this?

00:39:04.770 --> 00:39:08.202 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: Well, it's missing in
the tank which was over there--

00:39:08.202 --> 00:39:09.410 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: It's a little stove.

00:39:09.410 --> 00:39:11.140 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: A portable stove.

00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:13.760 align:middle line:10%
And you get a gas bottle
with a little pump

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:17.020 align:middle line:10%
that goes in the gas bottle
and that hooks into this stove.

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:18.060 align:middle line:10%
And this stove--

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:19.310 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Propane?

00:39:19.310 --> 00:39:22.600 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: No, it's a white
gas-- which is Coleman fuel,

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:26.150 align:middle line:84%
or white gas-- and
it folds up tiny.

00:39:26.150 --> 00:39:28.560 align:middle line:84%
And this is a back
country standard.

00:39:28.560 --> 00:39:31.334 align:middle line:84%
Another MSR product, it's
used all over the world.

00:39:31.334 --> 00:39:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And they have a little
different version

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:37.240 align:middle line:84%
that will burn kerosene, jet
fuel, alcohol, and gasoline

00:39:37.240 --> 00:39:38.240 align:middle line:90%
all in one single stove.

00:39:38.240 --> 00:39:39.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Just to do
some emergency cooking

00:39:39.710 --> 00:39:40.350 align:middle line:90%
and stuff like that.

00:39:40.350 --> 00:39:41.540 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Well, it'll
boil your water.

00:39:41.540 --> 00:39:42.890 align:middle line:90%
It'll purify your water.

00:39:42.890 --> 00:39:45.210 align:middle line:84%
It'll melt snow and
it'll cook food.

00:39:45.210 --> 00:39:46.960 align:middle line:84%
So it will do all of
those things for you.

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:49.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Got some emails here
for you, Matt, of the time

00:39:49.340 --> 00:39:50.140 align:middle line:90%
we have left.

00:39:50.140 --> 00:39:52.770 align:middle line:84%
Carol from Montana
would like to know

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:54.980 align:middle line:84%
if there is one future
threat that concerns

00:39:54.980 --> 00:39:57.010 align:middle line:90%
you more than anything else.

00:39:57.010 --> 00:39:58.230 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: The two.

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:01.330 align:middle line:84%
The ecological one
we talked about.

00:40:01.330 --> 00:40:04.010 align:middle line:84%
The solar storm is
guaranteed to happen.

00:40:04.010 --> 00:40:06.787 align:middle line:84%
EMP is possible, but the solar
storm is absolutely guaranteed.

00:40:06.787 --> 00:40:08.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It will happen one day.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:09.180 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: It will happen.

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:11.700 align:middle line:84%
We're overdue, and
that's guaranteed.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:14.450 align:middle line:84%
And the fact that we have not
protected our nuclear power

00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:17.010 align:middle line:84%
plants so that they're
going to run out of fuel

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:18.635 align:middle line:84%
and they're going to
start melting down

00:40:18.635 --> 00:40:21.090 align:middle line:84%
and that it's a
fixable problem, I'd

00:40:21.090 --> 00:40:23.200 align:middle line:84%
say that solar storm is
the one thing because it's

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:24.330 align:middle line:90%
so guaranteed to happen.

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:26.474 align:middle line:90%
That's what I worry about most.

00:40:26.474 --> 00:40:28.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And again, these
items here you think

00:40:28.390 --> 00:40:32.080 align:middle line:84%
are very critically
important in a pack?

00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:35.030 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Well, these items
are critically important.

00:40:35.030 --> 00:40:37.560 align:middle line:84%
And I have a list of
about 30 or 40 items

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:40.100 align:middle line:84%
that is available online
or in both my books,

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:45.460 align:middle line:84%
"When Technology Fails" and
"When Disaster Strikes."

00:40:45.460 --> 00:40:47.250 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Where do
we go in the future?

00:40:47.250 --> 00:40:48.630 align:middle line:90%
What happens next for us?

00:40:48.630 --> 00:40:53.680 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Well, I believe
that human beings have

00:40:53.680 --> 00:40:57.900 align:middle line:84%
this amazing ability
to be flexible,

00:40:57.900 --> 00:41:00.352 align:middle line:84%
and that there's a basic
goodness in human beings.

00:41:00.352 --> 00:41:02.310 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe that
humans are basically evil.

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:04.750 align:middle line:90%
I believe that they're good.

00:41:04.750 --> 00:41:09.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm concerned that the
natural trends on our planet

00:41:09.790 --> 00:41:11.860 align:middle line:84%
are going to
collapse the systems

00:41:11.860 --> 00:41:14.340 align:middle line:84%
and it will kill our planet
as far as human beings are

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:15.140 align:middle line:90%
concerned.

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:16.500 align:middle line:84%
There will be plenty
of animal life

00:41:16.500 --> 00:41:17.874 align:middle line:84%
and different
lives that survive.

00:41:17.874 --> 00:41:22.350 align:middle line:84%
But human beings, maybe none of
us will, maybe some of us will,

00:41:22.350 --> 00:41:25.150 align:middle line:84%
but it won't be in a way
that we look forward to.

00:41:25.150 --> 00:41:27.570 align:middle line:84%
I believe that we can
change this course.

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:29.840 align:middle line:84%
That we're headed for
the giant train wreck,

00:41:29.840 --> 00:41:31.560 align:middle line:84%
we're headed for
collapse, but I believe

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:33.130 align:middle line:90%
that we can change this.

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:35.260 align:middle line:10%
And I've got a little
list of 10 things

00:41:35.260 --> 00:41:39.980 align:middle line:10%
that we must do, I believe, if
we're going to actually avoid

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:41.480 align:middle line:10%
collapsing the planet.

00:41:41.480 --> 00:41:44.990 align:middle line:10%
Now, the hard part
is that it's going

00:41:44.990 --> 00:41:47.140 align:middle line:10%
to require some real
changes and it's

00:41:47.140 --> 00:41:49.306 align:middle line:10%
going to require
cooperation of the planet

00:41:49.306 --> 00:41:50.430 align:middle line:10%
to make the changes happen.

00:41:50.430 --> 00:41:51.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Give us just
a few highlights.

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:51.670 align:middle line:90%
>>STEIN: OK.

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:52.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We only have
time for a couple.

00:41:52.220 --> 00:41:54.180 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: Change
the tax structure.

00:41:54.180 --> 00:41:59.340 align:middle line:84%
We have to make it financially
suicidal for companies to do

00:41:59.340 --> 00:42:02.449 align:middle line:90%
things in nonsustainable ways.

00:42:02.449 --> 00:42:03.990 align:middle line:84%
So we have to penalize
companies that

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:07.180 align:middle line:84%
are doing things the wrong way,
and support companies doing

00:42:07.180 --> 00:42:08.360 align:middle line:90%
it the right way.

00:42:08.360 --> 00:42:10.130 align:middle line:84%
We have to rebuild
our cities and homes

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:13.360 align:middle line:84%
for maximum sustainability,
for minimum energy use.

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:15.930 align:middle line:84%
We have to rebuild our
railways and our mass transit.

00:42:15.930 --> 00:42:19.250 align:middle line:84%
Because how can we get around
if gas is $10 a gallon,

00:42:19.250 --> 00:42:20.750 align:middle line:90%
or $15 a gallon?

00:42:20.750 --> 00:42:22.480 align:middle line:90%
Rebuild our industries.

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:27.750 align:middle line:84%
We can put America back to work
rebuilding America and leading

00:42:27.750 --> 00:42:30.210 align:middle line:84%
the world in the
sustainability issue.

00:42:30.210 --> 00:42:35.110 align:middle line:84%
Unregulated capitalism-- if
we continue doing business

00:42:35.110 --> 00:42:37.520 align:middle line:84%
in a way that says
the maximum profit

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:41.935 align:middle line:84%
wins, then it will mean
using our natural resources

00:42:41.935 --> 00:42:44.980 align:middle line:84%
of the planet for maximum
profit as fast as possible

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:46.960 align:middle line:84%
with as little
regulation as possible

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:49.790 align:middle line:84%
so we can make the most money
before the world dies on us.

00:42:49.790 --> 00:42:52.145 align:middle line:84%
And we can't continue
doing business that way.

00:42:52.145 --> 00:42:55.590 align:middle line:84%
We have to fund and support
renewable energy development.

00:42:55.590 --> 00:42:58.890 align:middle line:84%
We have to eliminate
population growth.

00:42:58.890 --> 00:43:01.830 align:middle line:84%
This is a huge one that's
taboo to talk about.

00:43:01.830 --> 00:43:03.520 align:middle line:84%
The reality is
that from the time

00:43:03.520 --> 00:43:07.010 align:middle line:84%
Jesus walked the earth until
Abraham Lincoln was born,

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:10.160 align:middle line:84%
more people were added to
our world in the last decade

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:11.960 align:middle line:84%
than from Jesus to
Abraham Lincoln.

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:12.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And it's
getting bigger--

00:43:12.340 --> 00:43:13.160 align:middle line:84%
>>STEIN: We can't
keep doing that.

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:14.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --and
bigger and bigger.

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:19.150 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: We passed the
point of sustainability

00:43:19.150 --> 00:43:22.580 align:middle line:10%
in the planet in 1975, and
we had half the population

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:24.710 align:middle line:10%
we had then than we have now.

00:43:24.710 --> 00:43:26.730 align:middle line:84%
When I was a kid and
you were a kid in 1960,

00:43:26.730 --> 00:43:28.050 align:middle line:90%
we had three billion people.

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:30.470 align:middle line:90%
We're up to 7.4 billion now.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:35.180 align:middle line:10%
They're projecting in 30 years
it's going to eight to nine,

00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:36.870 align:middle line:10%
possibly a high variant.

00:43:36.870 --> 00:43:39.065 align:middle line:10%
If they don't do things
right, could be 10 or 11.

00:43:39.065 --> 00:43:40.690 align:middle line:10%
I don't honestly
don't think we'll ever

00:43:40.690 --> 00:43:43.030 align:middle line:10%
reach that, because I think
the planet can't stand it.

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:43.920 align:middle line:84%
I think it's going
to fall apart.

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:45.711 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And the
important thing right now,

00:43:45.711 --> 00:43:48.250 align:middle line:84%
Matt, based on what
I'm hearing from you,

00:43:48.250 --> 00:43:52.630 align:middle line:84%
is to get this little ability
taken care of right now.

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:56.151 align:middle line:84%
Put a nice pack together for
an emergency and just be safe.

00:43:56.151 --> 00:43:57.900 align:middle line:10%
Matt, thanks for being
on "Beyond Belief."

00:43:57.900 --> 00:43:59.180 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: It's been
such a pleasure,

00:43:59.180 --> 00:44:00.250 align:middle line:10%
and thank you so much.

00:44:00.250 --> 00:44:00.560 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: I appreciate it.

00:44:00.560 --> 00:44:02.434 align:middle line:10%
>>STEIN: Nice to meet
you, George, in person.

